class_description:
The map table is modeled after NSDictionary with the following differences:
Keys and/or values are optionally held “weakly” such that entries are removed when one of the objects is reclaimed.
Its keys or values may be copied on input or may use pointer identity for equality and hashing.
It can contain arbitrary pointers (its contents are not constrained to being objects).
You can configure an NSMapTable instance to operate on arbitrary pointers and not just objects, although typically you are encouraged to use the C function API for void * pointers. The object-based API (such as setObject(_:forKey:)) will not work for non-object pointers without type-casting.
When configuring map tables, note that only the options listed in NSMapTableOptions guarantee that the rest of the API will work correctly—including copying, archiving, and fast enumeration. While other NSPointerFunctions options are used for certain configurations, such as to hold arbitrary pointers, not all combinations of the options are valid. With some combinations the map table may not work correctly, or may not even be initialized correctly.
NSMapTable is not suitable for subclassing.

Methods.method_description: Returns all of the keys in the specified map table.

return_description: An array object containing all the keys in table. This function should be called only when table keys are objects, not when they’re any other type of pointer.

return_description: An array object containing all the values in table. This function should be called only when table values are objects, not when they’re any other type of pointer.

return_description: true if the keys and corresponding values of table1 and table2 are the same, and the two tables are the same size, otherwise false.

Methods.method_description: Used when finished with an enumerator.
Methods.method_declar: func NSEndMapTableEnumeration(_ enumerator: UnsafeMutablePointer<NSMapEnumerator>)

Methods.method_description: Deletes the specified map table.

params.param_description: A reference to a map table structure.

Methods.method_description: Inserts a key-value pair into the specified table.
Methods.method_declar: func NSMapInsert(_ table: NSMapTable<AnyObject, AnyObject>, _ key: UnsafeRawPointer?, _ value: UnsafeRawPointer?)

Methods.method_description: Inserts a key-value pair into the specified table.
Methods.method_declar: func NSMapInsertIfAbsent(_ table: NSMapTable<AnyObject, AnyObject>, _ key: UnsafeRawPointer?, _ value: UnsafeRawPointer?) -> UnsafeMutableRawPointer?

return_description: If key matches a key already in table, the preexisting value; otherwise, key and value are added to table and returns NULL.

Methods.method_description: Inserts a key-value pair into the specified table if the pair had not been previously added.
Methods.method_declar: func NSMapInsertKnownAbsent(_ table: NSMapTable<AnyObject, AnyObject>, _ key: UnsafeRawPointer?, _ value: UnsafeRawPointer?)

Methods.method_description: Removes a key and corresponding value from the specified table.
Methods.method_declar: func NSMapRemove(_ table: NSMapTable<AnyObject, AnyObject>, _ key: UnsafeRawPointer?)

Methods.method_description: Returns a Boolean value that indicates whether the next map-table pair in the enumeration are set.
Methods.method_declar: func NSNextMapEnumeratorPair(_ enumerator: UnsafeMutablePointer<NSMapEnumerator>, _ key: UnsafeMutablePointer<UnsafeMutableRawPointer?>?, _ value: UnsafeMutablePointer<UnsafeMutableRawPointer?>?) -> Bool

return_description: false if enumerator has already iterated over all the elements in the table that enumerator is associated with; otherwise, sets key and value to match the next key-value pair in the table and returns true.
